{"id":"1810.11540","submitter":"Brian Street","authors":"Brian Street","title":"Sub-Hermitian Geometry and the Quantitative Newlander-Nirenberg Theorem","comments":"v5: 62 pages, final version, to appear in Adv. Math","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CV math.AP math.CA math.DG","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Given a finite collection of $C^1$ complex vector fields on a $C^2$ manifold\n$M$ such that they and their complex conjugates span the complexified tangent\nspace at every point, the classical Newlander-Nirenberg theorem gives\nconditions on the vector fields so that there is a complex structure on $M$\nwith respect to which the vector fields are $T^{0,1}$. In this paper, we give\nintrinsic, diffeomorphic invariant, necessary and sufficient conditions on the\nvector fields so that they have a desired level of regularity with respect to\nthis complex structure (i.e., smooth, real analytic, or have Zygmund regularity\nof some finite order). By addressing this in a quantitative way we obtain a\nholomorphic analog of the quantitative theory of sub-Riemannian geometry\ninitiated by Nagel, Stein, and Wainger. We call this sub-Hermitian geometry.\nMoreover, we proceed more generally and obtain similar results for manifolds\nwhich have an associated formally integrable elliptic structure. This allows us\nto introduce a setting which generalizes both the real and complex theories.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 26 Oct 2018 21:50:01 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 4 Jan 2019 17:36:58 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 15 Mar 2019 18:34:42 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Thu, 6 Feb 2020 19:47:07 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Thu, 9 Apr 2020 18:30:11 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-04-13"}
